<node TEXT="Role of TCs" ID="ID_1915732922" CREATED="1464005231548" MODIFIED="1464005238774" NUMBERED="true">
<node TEXT="The author (principal investigator) is experienced in the theoretical and computational investigations concerned with the wetting of liquids on solid surfaces. He was involved in the development of molecular simulation-based approaches to calculate the solid-fluid interfacial properties \cite{rane2011understanding}. These methods were used to get insights into the wetting behavior of novel fluids /cite{rane2014understanding} on solid surfaces. The above studies also highlighted the influence of chemical nature of solid and fluid on the temperature dependence of wetting behavior \cite{rane2014usingthesis}. In Figure \ref{crystal_chi_d2VdN2_dgdT} we show $\frac{\mathrm{d}(\gamma_{\mathrm{sv}}-\gamma_{\mathrm{sl}})}{\mathrm{d}T}$ vs $\gamma_{\mathrm{sv}}-\gamma_{\mathrm{sl}}$ for a model fluid on two different crystalline surfaces. The difference in trends indicate the importance of the topography of the solid surface and the potential for designing surfaces with desired thermal response of wetting." ID="ID_1986819986" CREATED="1464005240012" MODIFIED="1464447312212" NUMBERED="true"/>
<node TEXT="Coming to the transverse correlations (TCs), the author was involved in investigating their role in the solvation of small solutes near liquid-vapor interface \cite{rane2016understanding,rane2016using}. The computational methods and the theoretical framework used in those studies are also applicable in the proposed project. For example, in Figure \ref{solute_chi_d2VdN2} we show the local compressibility $\chi(z)$ and $\frac{\mathrm{d^2}V}{\mathrm{d}N^{\mathrm{2}}}$ for a liquid-vapor interface in presence and absence of a fixed solute. For a system with solute, we observe a smaller peak for $\chi(z)$ and $\frac{\mathrm{d^2}V}{\mathrm{d}N^{\mathrm{2}}}&gt;0$. This indicates the dampening of the TCs by the solute. Similar quantities will be also calculated in the proposed project. One may also recollect from our earlier discussion that a single solute molecule positioned near liquid-vapor interface can be interpreted as a hypothetical solid surface that is infinitely sparse. Thus, the contribution of TCs to the solvation free energy $\Delta\mu$ is analogous to their contribution to $\gamma_{\mathrm{sv}}-\gamma_{\mathrm{sl}}$. Preliminary derivations also suggest that the dampening of TCs by the solute affects $\frac{\mathrm{d}\Delta\mu}{\mathrm{d}T}$. This implies that the dampening of TCs by the solid surface atoms will affect \frac{\mathrm{d}(\gamma_{\mathrm{sv}}-\gamma_{\mathrm{sl}})}{\mathrm{d}T}$. In fact, preliminary observations (Figure \ref{crystal_chi_d2VdN2_dgdT}) do indicate a correlation between $\chi$ near different crystal surfaces, $\frac{\mathrm{d^2}V}{\mathrm{d}N^{\mathrm{2}}}$, and the trends in $\frac{\mathrm{d}(\gamma_{\mathrm{sv}}-\gamma_{\mathrm{sl}})}{\mathrm{d}T}$ vs $\gamma_{\mathrm{sv}}-\gamma_{\mathrm{sl}}$." ID="ID_765596101" CREATED="1464076040496" MODIFIED="1464166832679" NUMBERED="true"/>
<node TEXT="On the algorithmic side, the author was involved in the development of transition matrix Monte Carlo (TMMC) based simulation approaches \cite{rane2013monte,rane2013using}. The TMMC-like schemes have potential to reduce computational expenses in variety of investigations, especially when combined with advanced algorithms \cite{ching2008higher}. During the abovementioned projects, the author was also involved in developing computer programs to perform simulations, as well as to analyze the results. Concerning the analysis, the author has been also involved in developing methods to extract important thermodynamic properties from the existing simulation data  \cite{rane2014usingthesis,rane2016using}. This experience will be useful in getting important physical insights from the high-precision data that will be generated during the proposed project." ID="ID_1286431111" CREATED="1464079327410" MODIFIED="1464091263218" NUMBERED="true"/>
</node>
</node>
